oody/loner\u201d description?\n3. **Candidate\u202fB or D:** Any data on their willingness to pursue further training or professional development?\n**Tentative assessment**\nGiven the high priority of **reliability** and **calmness under pressure** for long\u2011distance international flights, Candidate\u202fB currently stands out with a solid reliability record, proven crisis composure, and valuable technical skills (weather assessment, computer proficiency). The main drawback is his pretentious communication style, which could be mitigated with crew\u2011resource\u2011management training, but the data does not provide any compensating teamwork strengths.\nTherefore, based on the information available, I am inclined to vote for **Candidate\u202fB** as the best overall fit for the long\u2011distance pilot role, while remaining open to revising this view if additional evidence (especially regarding decision\u2011making speed for B or positive teamwork for D) emerges.\nMETADATA_JSON:\n{\"agent\": \"agent_2\", \"vote\": \"Candidate B\"}", "thoughts": "We have just asked Agent 1 for reliability info, got answer confirming none. Now we need to produce our public contribution. We need to consider the discussion so far: Agent 3 gave summary and tentative vote for B, asked for decision-making speed for B and teamwork for D. Agent 1 just answered reliability for A and C (none). We as Agent 2 need to contribute: we have our own knowledge set (the original list). We should maybe provide additional attributes not yet covered: e.g., technical competence, calmness, decision-making, teamwork, etc. Also we can answer Agent 3's open questions if we have info: decision-making speed/quality for B? The original list includes: \"Candidate B keeps calm in a crisis.\" \"Candidate B is known to be 100% reliable.\" \"Candidate B is good at assessing weather conditions.\" \"Candidate B has excellent computer skills.\" No explicit decision-making speed. So we cannot answer that. For D teamwor